description.text:
A wall mount for iPads. Here's an excerpt from the original description:

"Not quickly removable but very secure."

I wanted my iPad to be "quickly removable", so I modified the design so that the top holder can easily be taken off without the need for a screwdriver, and without sacrificing grip security.
However, if you've already used the original design, this remix sadly moves the screw position, requiring a new hole in your wall. Sorry about that.

(For good measure, I also added a loop on the left side to hold the cable. Obviously wouldn't work with a lightning connector.)

Here's the rest of the original description, I haven't been able to test it on anything but an iPad 2 either.

"Designed for iPad 2 but should be scalable to fit newer versions. I haven't tried, but here are my best guesses for the scale factors, they should be close at least. Not sure about the button location.

iPad 1 0.528" - scale 153%

To do this exercise properly, you need to update parameter(s) in the model to match your printer (which is really not how this should work, but).

Will write this up as a weblog post, at some point...

In my latest (versioned in Onshape) iteration, got down to 0.2mm in gap between parts, with a parameter in the model, which ... is quite wrong. The parameter should be part of the printer profile given to the slicer. Still.

From the Document Description (in Onshape):
The #overfill parameter is used to adjust the amount lines of plastic laid down by an additive 3D printer are a bit wider than where the plastic is meant to land. For example, a 12mm circle (in the x-y plane) when printed on my current printer measures a bit over 12.1mm, so I set #overfill to 0.1mm (for my printer).

This #overfill number should be zero (the CAD model should not have adjustments for the printer). But the state of the art with 3D printers is not that advanced. (In fact it is much like using on-paper printers in the 1980s and 90s.)

The clearance between each cylinder and the frame varies between 0.1mm and 0.7mm, in steps of #dxy_gap (which is set to 0.1mm). If you have an ultra-precise printer, you might try a smaller #dxy_gap value. On my printer I can free all but the last cylinder, and the gap between cylinder and the frame is close to what is specified in the model.

I suspect the #overfill value varies with temperature, layer height, filament, extrusion speed, etc. But ... have to start somewhere. :)

remixed_from.title: How to make a Hobbed bolt

title: BoltHobber - A Hobbed bolt maker - All M8 version

description.text:
First of all, thanks so much Mr. Heinz, your design is amazing. This is a full M8 version of the original BoltHobber. In other words, it is designed for:
  • M8 tap screw
  • 608 skate bearings
  • M8 adjustment screw and nut
  • M8 hobbed bolt

Print it dense like:
  • 60% honeycomb infill.
  • 4 perimeters
    • Metal parts:
  • 4 608 bearings
  • 1 M8 adjustment screw (longer than 50mm) and nut
  • 1 M8 screw (Hobbed bolt)
  • 1 M5 washer or another piece of metal
    • Step-by-step:
  • Insert the M8 nut on its housing located on "slide" part;
  • Screw the adjustment screw just to put it in place;
  • Insert the only the internal 608 bearing on slide part;
    The other 608 pair will be attached on tap screw body.
  • Insert both 608 bearing on base;

• Place the M5 washer (or metal piece) on top of the Base bridge.
    It is necessary to distribute the force along the plastic
  • Assembly both printed parts as the picture shows;
  • Insert the Hobbed bolt candidate through the 608 bearings.
    Make some measures on your extruder to make sure that the channel will be done on the right distance from the screw head.
    You can add some washers to adjust the distance.
  • Screw two M8 nuts to fix it in place;
  • Now add the remaining 608 bearing on the tap screw body and insert it on slide part;
  • Adjust the distance/pressure by the top M8 screw;
  • Turn the tap screw and follow the results on the small window;
  • You can repeat the steps 6 and 7 until you reach the desired depth.
  • Release the adjustment screw and pull the tap screw;
  • Release the two Hobbed bolt nuts and pull it from slide part;
  • The 608 bearing will not slide trough the screw due the burrs, so grind it off and the bearing will pass.
    • Now, be happy with your powerful-not-expensive Hobbed bolt :-)

title: Flying Saucer UFO Fidget Spinner Hand Spinner

description.text:
Kids are obsessed with fidget spinners these days... I wanted one that looked like a flying saucer, but not a traditional spinner. This model has a center that spins, but the top and bottom of the saucer are fixed on the peg. Requires 1 608 spinner bearing. The center section has 8 M8 or 5/16 Nuts for weight that are printed into the model. I paused the print at layer 63 to insert the hardware (.12 layer height).

If your fingers are small enough - mine are not, you can hold the center and spin the outer part too, so I added holes for 4 608 bearings to weight the top, if you don't want to weight the outside, you can print 2 of the part labeled bottom.

This works well as a propelled top too, that's my favorite way to use it. I spin the center section as hard as I can while holding the top and bottom dome, then set it on a counter and the top and bottom begin to accelerate and it will spin on the bottom dome for quite some time.

My second version which is more like a traditional fidget spinner is posted at this link
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2327987

Print
1 Top, 1 bottom (or 2 bottom or top), 1 center, 1 peg, and 4-6 of the washers to space the center so that it does not have friction with the top and bottom. I have not gotten this to work friction free yet, but it does spin pretty well.

description.text: A card and token organizer for Rallyman, will accommodate Dirt expansion as well. Tray1 is for 1st through 3rd gear cards; Tray 2 is for 4th, 4th, and Shortcut (K) cards; Tray 3 is for time bonus and damage tokens; Tray 4 is for dice and MRC's. Card trays are sized for sleeved cards.

20% (doesn't matter)

Notes:

Printed Tray1 and revised dimensions based on test fit. Haven't yet reprinted 1 or printed 2-4. Tray3 may need a small amount of support along the lower portion of the curve.

Update 2017-05-18: Printed revised trays 1-4 and am very happy with them. Tray 3 definitely needs support.

Update 2017-05-25: Added lids for the trays at the request of a player. I have not printed these, nor do I plan to (not enough room left in my box). Please let me know how they worked if you print them.

Update 2017-05-26: Ok, so I decided to print lid1. Upon printing, realized that the wall thickness (@ 2mm) would be too thick to lay the trays in the bottom of the box in my preferred orientation. I reduced the thickness to 1.2mm and also extended the catch tabs by 0.025mm to increase the grip on the tray. Mine fit perfectly, but I figured if it's too tight, it's easy to sand them down a bit, but much harder to add material if they're loose.

Update 2017-07-03: It turns out Lid 3 was too short lengthwise. It's fixed now.

G90 ; Set CNC to absolute mode
M83 ; Set extruder to relative mode

G1 X20 Y230 F7800.000 ; Move to a spot that isnt above the build plate

G1 E-125 F1800 ; Retract current extruder fast

T[next_extruder] ; Switch to other extruder

G1 E130 F1800 ; Extrude fast
G1 E25 F120 ; Extrude slow

M82 ; Set extruder back to absolute mode

description.text:
Update: Turned on the customizer feature. Change the "magic_distance" to some other value if you want the jig to be a different length.

The AM8 design requires both Z "towers" to be positioned 127mm from the back of the frame, and holding a ruler while holding everything together and tightening screws is a pain in the ass.

OpenSCAD file is included, so you can customize the design to different lengths if you're building a larger-bed printer or whatever.

Enjoy the build!

description.text:
We are the students of Passerelles Numeriques Philippines, Class 2019.
During our 3D training summer class, we have 3D printed a Filipino board game called "Game of the Generals".
GoG is an educational war game invented in the Philippines by Sofronio H. Pasola, Jr. in 1970. Its Filipino name is "Salpakan" and it is designed for two players, each controlling an army, and an arbiter or the referee to decide the results of the challenges. It can be played within 20 to 30 minutes depending upon the players.

Sharing with everyone our work so that they could also print their own Game of the Generals.

  • Before saving your file, you must check first the layers of your object in Cura to avoid errors while printing.
  • Calibrate your printer properly .
  • Always keep the build plate of the printer clean.
  • Do post processing after printing the object for better results.

These are the materials that we used in the post processing : cutter, ruler, shoes glue and the sand paper. We used the shoes glue to paste the printed game board squares in the game board. This is the finished product.

We designed every piece in Sketch Up, export in STL format and import it in CURA. Then, save it as gcode.

  • Printing duration: 10 mins. per piece

Game board Squares

  • Color yellow
  • 20mm by 25mm
  • 0.4 thickness

  • Printing Duration: one hour

Game Board at the same time Game Box

  • Wooden type design

The objective of the game is to eliminate or capture the Flag of the opponent, or to maneuver one's Flag to the far edge of the board (the opposing back rank), subject to the following conditions.
The Flag, if challenged, is eliminated by any opposing piece, including the opposing and challenging Flag.
If a player's Flag is eliminated by a challenge, that player loses the game.
The Flag that challenges the opponent's Flag wins the challenge and thus also wins the game.
When the Flag successfully reaches the opponent's back rank, it has to survive one more turn without being challenged before it can declare a victory.
If a Flag reaches the opposing back rank and there is no adjacent opposing piece that can challenge it, the Flag wins the game immediately.
If a Flag reaches the opposing back rank directly adjacent to an opposing piece, and that piece does not challenge the Flag immediately on the opponent's subsequent turn, then that Flag wins the game.
Any player may reveal his Flag at any time and for any reason; play can then continue; most often, a player reveals his Flag after it has already secured victory at the opposing back rank.

title: Titan Aero Upgrade for Original Prusa i3 MK2(s)

description.text:
Why do you want this Titan Aero upgrade for your Prusa i3 MK2?

Benefits:

  • Lighter, more compact assembly with center of mass closer to axis -> higher print speeds, more immune to knocks
    • see video: http://e3d-online.com/Titan-Aero-Standard-175-12V
  • 440 cc more build volume due to shorter stack
    • Full X and Y range with additional Z height
  • Shorter filament path means less ooze and better handles flexible filaments
  • Easier manual loading and unloading of filament
  • Simpler nozzle changes with no disassembly
  • Better print visibility for progress or identify issues
  • Manual tension adjust, cleaning, maintenance without tools/disassembly
  • Enhanced part cooling

Minimal changes to stock:

  • NO FIRMWARE CHANGES

  • These 4 printed parts + 4 screws + Titan Aero + Motor^

    ^ This is designed to use a short body nema 17, not the stock unit.
    Motor body length must be <= 23mm , such as: https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00PNEQ79Q/
    If you want to use a motor with 24-26mm body, such as http://e3d-online.com/Electrical/Stepper-Motors/NEMA17-Titan-Slimline, you lose 3mm of X range. See notes at end of build section. You may need to adjust currents as well (see end).

Print (slic3r PE instructions):

I recommend printing x carriage, aero, pinda mount together
Print in ASA or ABS. PETG can work. Because I am taking advantage of the shorter Titan stack to improve Z, the heater block is closer to the x carriage, so I recommend the e3d silicone sock. The glass transition is roughly: ABS/ASA 100C, PETG 80C, PLA 60C.

  • aero mount -> object settings: infill 80% or 100% for strength (other two can be normal infill I suspect)
  • add supports -> use on build plate only which should add very little support
  • also add brim, maybe 8mm, to help corners hold with ABS/ASA

I printed these in ABS and they came out pretty well. First clean your bed with alcohol and then acetone. I used a 0.4 nozzle, 0.2mm layer, 20% infill, 255C nozzle and 105C bed, no fan. I also put a large plastic tub over the printer as a cheap enclosure to trap heat. I had to clean up the pinda mount slot and aero mount center pin with a knife. Otherwise everything fit nicely.

Blower mount can be printed in PLA, with supports.
I have had good luck with these support settings on PLA

  • contact Z: 0.15
  • pattern angle: 20
  • interface spacing: 0.5
  • XY: 70%

Build (assumes you are upgrading from stock):

Please read through first to know the order of steps and take your time.

  1. Unwire the extruder wire bundle from the RAMBO. Remove two screws on X motor to loosen and remove belt. Cut the zip ties on x-carriage. Remove stock extruder + x carriage.
  2. Fit pins of aero mount into holes in X-carriage and screw two ends down with 2 M3x20 (or longer) and washers and nuts, very snug. Screw head fits in recess on back, nut and washer in front. Make sure base of mount is flush against carriage all the way across.
  3. X-carriage mounts like stock onto the X-axis rods (see steps X.8 - X.11 in manual) with zip-tie to linear bearings. Make sure upper left bearing (nearest X motor) is all the way to the outside against the lip of the X-carriage so it most clearance for filament gear.
  4. Insert Nema-17 short body on left side of aero mount with wires toward back and route through wire channel. If your motor has a plug connector, you will need to orient to the front and run wires around to the back. There are zip-tie channels on bottom edge of aero mount to help.
  5. Mount titan on right following instructions at https://wiki.e3d-online.com/wiki/Titan_Aero#Assembly_Steps. You will use no spacer and the short set of screws. Don’t mount heatsink fan yet.
  6. Install cartridges in heater block opposite of what is shown on e3d, so wires exit other direction.
  7. Make sure screws are snug and check clearance of filament gear in slot and between linear bearings on back of X-carriage.
  8. Insert PINDA into pinda mount and add two screws and nuts loosely for now.
  9. Screw pinda mount onto X-carriage, lining up arrows, using M3x25, nut optional. Rotate PINDA body so wire is toward back (it is not centered) to get best clearance to heatsink. Route wire through channel on X-carriage.
  10. Mount heatsink fan onto heatsink according to e3d instructions and route wires next to PINDA wire in channel.
  11. Mount blower fan into blower mount by tipping outlet into mount and rotate to snap in top. Screw with M3x25, head in recess, nut on left.
  12. Attach blower mount using ends of the two M3x20 screws holding the aero mount, outside of the existing nuts. There should be room for second nut. See renderings for reference.
  13. Route blower wires alongside the motor wires in channel.
  14. Angle the heater block so the nozzle is nearest the blower outlet and clamp screw is nearest the PINDA. Both the heater and thermistor wires should point right back through the bottom wire channel. Optional: tape piece of aluminum foil to X carriage in recess behind heater and through bottom wire channel to deflect heat, especially if using PETG.
  15. Add e3d silicone sock over heater block.
  16. Slide X carriage to extreme left and right and make sure end-stop clicks and no other obstructions. NOTE: if you have MK2S, you may need to Dremel off a bit of the X motor end support if the corner of the motor hits. See photo, marked in green. The pancake motor above should not require this.
  17. Bundle wires and run back to the RAMBO. You can follow the MK2S instruction manual or I recommend cable chain for the extruder, such as: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2311596
    NOTE: you must wire backwards or reverse plug into RAMBO to make extruder turn correct direction since you've added a gear in the path.
  18. Reattach belt and screw in X motor to restore tension. Double check no binding on full range of X.

If you are building for a 25mm motor, print two extend and one bumper piece. Clip the bumper onto the x-carriage where it contacts the end stop. Add the extend pieces to the blower mount by inserting into blower mount holes and screwing down extender using an extra washer. If you have MK2s, you will need to grind a bit off the motor end support as described above.

Software:

Only change required is to change extruder steps to account for 3:1 gearing.

Simplest:
add this to your start g-code in slic3r 

M92 E418.5

Note: if you are using a 0.9 step motor, you need to double the number above..

Better:
use the command above and then perform an extruder calibration to adjust value as necessary. Once satisfied, you can commit the change to eeprom using the command from Pronterface or Octoprint terminal. This will make the firmware load/unload function correctly.

M500

Note: if you are using the e3d slim motor you may need to add this to your start g-code to increase the motor current:
M907 E900

History:
V1-V5: beta test versions to get kinks sorted out. Many thanks to spid303 for testing.

12/13/17: I added the step files for your hacking pleasure.

description.text:
The reason why I have to design the body mount spacers is because I needed to
adjust the front and rear stock body mounts because they are almost none
adjustable and I needed to adjust the body that I originally install onto
my Traxxas Slash 4x4 because there's an imbalance between the front and the
rear. So I was able to do some modification with some leftover parts from the
stock body mount so I use the extension body posts and cut it down to size so
I can raise the front a bit so I can have a balance between the front and the
rear of the vehicle so that problem is fixed until I install the RPM mud flaps
as a result I needed to adjust the rear body mount some more but I was not able
to do so so I needed to design the body mount spacers to address this problem
as a result I made the stock body mounts adjustable. If you wish to download
the bottom mount spacers and all you will need Screws at the minimum they
need to be about 3x20mm or longer depending upon what body that you are using
and the photos and the cad file should give you a idea how to install them
I did my best to explain how to install them with a photos so enjoy these
upgrades.

description.text:
I'm still very new at this so it's not as elegant as some of the other designs out there, but I noted a severe lack of Harry Potter themed fidgets (and the one I found was a bit large even for adult hands) so I'm making a few to share. I'm a Chapter Organizer of a community-based Harry Potter Alliance chapter and would be happy to see these getting spread throughout the HPA. Don't make them to sell for profit, but I'm OK with the design being used for fundraising purposes for HPA groups or other educational non-profits.

Designed in TinkerCAD, printed on a New Matter MOD-t (I think I used the fast pre-sets in the white one in the photo).

For others who want to make fidget spinners, I've found the best opening size for the bearing is 22.55mm - anything smaller requires a hammer to get the bearing in, anything bigger the bearing falls out. At that size, it can be pushed in with thumbs & seated into the plastic well by pressing on a table and is removable with effort but not likely to pop out.

My designs for spinners are not weighted after my husband lost control of one he made with nuts in the arms and nearly whacked our baby in the head with it. If you want to take this design and put in some ball bearings in the wings, go ahead and do it yourself. Don't ask me to do it, Mama says no.

description.text:
Was working on a concept for mounting my Logitech Webcam to my Lulzbot Taz 5 and came across wantmys2000's Dropcam Mount (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:745446). I like the bottom support bracket design but the arms and mounting plate don't meet my needs. I want to be able to extend the heated bed all the way to the end so need a arm design that can accommodate that. The mounting plate needs to support my Logitech WebCam. So with keeping the bottom mounting bracket, I redesigned the arms and created a 2 piece mount clamping block. Also I printed my pieces out of ABS due to the proximity of the heated bed.

Will need to print 2 of the Arms and rotate all pieces so that they lay flat. For the bottom support bracket, I bit the bullet and printed with supports so the mounting ends would be stronger with the outline being drawn with a 2mm wall.

I used x6 M3 heat-set inserts (https://www.mcmaster.com/#94180a333/=17nqddx)
and x6 M3 10mm hex screws (https://www.mcmaster.com/#socket-head-cap-screws/=17nqe5p)

I included a webcam POV pict as well.
If you like this design and do wind up printing it, please share your picts.

title: Parametric Z endstop mount and arm for Prusa i3 rework

description.text:
Z axis endstop mount and adjustment screw arm for a Prusa I3 rework with an extra-long extruder heat sink.

The endstop mount is designed to be attached to one of the Z axis motors, and the arm is designed to be attached to the Y axis motor above it.

Parameters allow the arm to be adjustable roughly 10mm on any axis so that it can precisely touch down on whatever model of endstop you use.

Versatility

Adding a longer heat sink to the Prusa i3 rework meant that the normal Z-axis endstop was far too short. I wanted a solution that would allow precise control over a wider range of settings, and allow for a variety of models of mechanical endstop.

This OpenSCAD model allows the user to easily and precisely place the end of an adjustment screw onto the contact of the endstop. Adjustments allow a variation of about 10mm on any axis.

description.text:
Gear spinner
First post!

Designed with Blender, printed on a Wanhao Duplicator i3.
One in a series of hand spinners I am working on.... more to come!

Required parts to build this spinner:
2 - Frames (3D printed)
3 - Outer Gears (3D printed)
1 - Inner Gear (3D Printed)
5 - Standard Bearings
2 - Washers (diameter matching the inner ring of the bearings)
1 - 1in screw

Printer Brand:

Wanhao

Printer:

Wanhao Duplicator i3 V2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2 or .3 (both tested)

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Bearings should fit into the frame pieces and the outer gears with some resistance. I like to gently guide the bearings into place using pliers (pressing down slightly on one side of the bearing, then the same on the other side, repeat).

When screwing the cap pieces together, be sure that the screw goes in straight. If the cap pieces are crooked when the screw it tightened, your spinner will not spin very well.

I find that the spinner works best when the cap pieces are tightened very well (inner gear should not move at all if you're holding either side of the cap) and that the frame pieces are secured to the middle of the bearing on both sides.

Degrease your bearings for better results.
Have fun, and post results, feedback, or suggestions.
